item.title: About
item.description: The California Weekly Pulse site was created and is maintained by the Stanford Data Lab. If you have any feedback, comments, or suggestions for improvements to this site, please email us.

item.title: Alameda County
item.description: Food insufficiency Unemployment Food insufficiency In the most recent survey period that ended March 13, an estimated 7.3% of Alameda County adults, or approximately 83,000 adults, lived in households experiencing food insufficiency. Using a model based upon data from the Food Security Supplement of the Current Population Survey, we estimate that in the most recent survey period, 6.7% of children, or approximately 22,200 children, experienced food insufficiency. Because the Household Pulse Survey does not provide data at the county level, we use a model to estimate county-level food insufficiency.

item.title: California
item.description: Overview Food insufficiency Rate over time Geography Demographics Reasons Severity Supplemental Nutrition Assitance Program (SNAP) and Special Supplementary Nutrition Assistance Program for Women, Infants, and Children (WIC) Free groceries Unemployment Rate over time Geography Overview The data on this site is derived from the U.S. Census Bureau Household Pulse Survey (HPS) and the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics Local Area Unemployment Statistics (LAUS). New HPS data is currently released every four weeks, and new LAUS data is released once a month.
